-- Chords

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'Dm7',
  'Dm7 adds a melancholic, sophisticated edge to D Minor. It is one of the most versatile seventh chords in music and appears constantly in jazz, soul, R&B, and blues.',
  'Dm7 is built from four notes: D (root), F (minor third), A (perfect fifth), and C (minor seventh). It is essentially a D Minor chord with the flat seventh (C) added on top. The addition of that C note softens the darkness of D Minor slightly and gives the chord a more complex, introspective quality — less stark than a bare minor chord, but still emotionally weighted. Dm7 is the ii7 chord in the key of C Major, which means it appears at the start of the famous ii-V-I jazz progression: Dm7 - G7 - Cmaj7. This three-chord movement is the backbone of jazz harmony and learning Dm7 is your entry point into that world. It also appears in the key of F Major as the vi7 chord, making it extremely common across many popular songs.',
  'The open position Dm7 is one of the easier seventh chords to play. Place your index finger across both the B and high E strings at the first fret (a small partial barre), then place your middle finger on the second fret of the G string. Strum from the D string downward — the open D string is your root bass note. The open A string should be avoided or muted. Practice the ii-V-I movement by playing Dm7, then G7, then C Major in sequence. This three-chord phrase is one of the most important harmonic movements in all of music and will train your ear to hear chord function.',
  'Index: partial barre B and high e strings, fret 1 | Middle: G string, fret 2 | Open: D | Mute: low E, A',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765151/Dm7_gbtr21.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'Em7',
  'Em7 is one of the most beautiful and commonly used chords on guitar. Its open, airy sound makes it a favorite in pop, folk, and R&B, and it is surprisingly easy to play.',
  'Em7 is built from four notes: E (root), G (minor third), B (perfect fifth), and D (minor seventh). The open D string provides the minor seventh naturally, meaning Em7 can be played with just two fingers — the same as E Minor — or even with no fingers at all using a completely open voicing. This makes it one of the most beginner-accessible seventh chords on the guitar. Em7 is the vi7 chord in the key of G Major and the ii7 chord in the key of D Major, making it appear frequently in songs written in those two very common guitar keys. Its sound is softer and more open than plain E Minor — the added D note creates a floating, unresolved quality that many songwriters find deeply appealing for introspective or atmospheric passages.',
  'The simplest Em7 voicing uses the same two-finger shape as E Minor — middle finger on the second fret of the A string, ring finger on the second fret of the D string — but lets the open G string ring freely instead of pressing it. All six strings ring open or fretted. Compare E Minor and Em7 by playing them back to back — notice how Em7 has a softer, more open and atmospheric quality. A one-finger version also exists: simply place your middle finger on the second fret of the A string alone and let all other strings ring open for a minimal but beautiful sound.',
  'Middle: A string, fret 2 | Ring: D string, fret 2 | Open: E, G (7th), B, high e',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765151/Em7_hgoqir.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'D6',
  'D6 adds a warm, jazzy sweetness to the standard D Major chord. It is used in jazz, blues, soul, and pop to add color and sophistication to chord progressions.',
  'D6 is built from four notes: D (root), F# (major third), A (perfect fifth), and B (major sixth). It is a D Major chord with the major sixth (B) added. The sixth interval gives the chord a vintage, slightly sweet quality that is immediately recognizable in jazz and classic pop recordings. Unlike dominant seventh chords which create tension and want to resolve, sixth chords have a stable, resolved sound with added color — making them useful as a resting point in a progression rather than a passing tension chord. D6 is particularly idiomatic on guitar because the B note is available as an open string, making some voicings very easy to play. It is the I6 chord in the key of D Major and commonly appears as a substitution for plain D Major when a player wants a slightly more sophisticated sound.',
  'A simple open position D6 voicing: place your index finger on the second fret of the G string and your middle finger on the second fret of the high E string. The open D, open B (the sixth!), and the fretted G and high E strings form the chord — strum from the D string down. Notice that the open B string is doing all the harmonic work of making this a sixth chord. Another voicing swaps the high E for the B string note placement. Experiment with using D6 wherever you would normally play D Major in a progression and notice how it adds a gentle warmth to the sound.',
  'Index: G string, fret 2 | Middle: high e string, fret 2 | Open: D, B (6th) | Mute: low E, A',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765154/D6_uvxc3r.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'E6',
  'E6 has a bright, vintage character that brings a jazz and soul flavor to standard E Major. It is widely used in R&B, jazz, and classic rock for added harmonic color.',
  'E6 is built from four notes: E (root), G# (major third), B (perfect fifth), and C# (major sixth). It is E Major with the major sixth (C#) added. Sixth chords sit in a harmonically stable place — unlike seventh chords that create tension, sixth chords feel resolved but richer and more colorful than plain triads. E6 has a warm, slightly vintage sound that is very characteristic of classic R&B and soul guitar playing. It appears as a I6 chord in the key of E Major and is often used as a more sophisticated replacement for plain E Major when a player wants to add harmonic interest without disrupting the flow of a progression. The C# note gives E6 a brightness that complements its already resonant open string voicing.',
  'A common open position E6 voicing keeps the standard E Major shape but adds the C# note. Place your index finger on the first fret of the G string, middle finger on the second fret of the A string, and ring finger on the second fret of the D string — same as open E Major — then add your pinky on the second fret of the B string to introduce the C# (the sixth). Alternatively, simply play the open E Major shape and add the C# on the B string with your pinky. Practice switching between E Major and E6 in the same position to hear how the added sixth note changes the chord color.',
  'Index: G string, fret 1 | Middle: A string, fret 2 | Ring: D string, fret 2 | Pinky: B string, fret 2 | Open: E, high e',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765152/E6_jspbam.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'Em6',
  'Em6 is a hauntingly beautiful chord that blends the darkness of E Minor with the brightness of a major sixth. It is a favorite in jazz, bossa nova, and film scores.',
  'Em6 is built from four notes: E (root), G (minor third), B (perfect fifth), and C# (major sixth). It is E Minor with a major sixth (C#) added — a seemingly contradictory combination of a minor third and a major sixth that produces a uniquely complex, bittersweet sound. The tension between the minor quality of the chord and the bright major sixth creates an emotional ambiguity that many composers and arrangers find deeply expressive. Em6 is common in jazz harmony, Brazilian bossa nova, and cinematic music where complex emotional textures are desired. It also appears in classical guitar repertoire and in the work of sophisticated pop songwriters. The chord has a slightly unresolved, searching quality that makes it compelling to listen to.',
  'A practical Em6 voicing builds on the open E Minor shape. Keep your middle and ring fingers on the second fret of the A and D strings as in E Minor, but add your index finger or pinky on the second fret of the B string to introduce the C# note (the major sixth). All remaining strings ring open. The open G string gives you the minor third and the open E strings anchor the root. Play the chord slowly and let all notes ring — listen carefully for the interplay between the minor G note and the major sixth C#. This chord rewards slow, deliberate playing.',
  'Middle: A string, fret 2 | Ring: D string, fret 2 | Pinky: B string, fret 2 | Open: E, G, high e',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765157/Em6_ihipii.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'Dm6',
  'Dm6 is a sophisticated and evocative chord that pairs D Minor darkness with a major sixth for a sound common in jazz, tango, and film noir-inspired music.',
  'Dm6 is built from four notes: D (root), F (minor third), A (perfect fifth), and B (major sixth). Like Em6, it combines a minor chord with a major sixth interval — an inherently complex pairing that creates a sound simultaneously dark and colorful. The B natural note (major sixth) sitting above the minor triad gives Dm6 a distinctive sound that is neither purely sad nor purely bright. It is extensively used in jazz chord-melody playing, bossa nova, and tango music. In classical guitar, Dm6 voicings appear frequently in Spanish-influenced repertoire. The chord has a particular affinity for descending bass line progressions where the sixth helps create smooth chromatic movement between chords. It also appears as a passing chord in minor key progressions where it adds harmonic sophistication.',
  'The open position Dm6 builds on D Minor. Place your index finger on the first fret of the high E string, middle finger on the second fret of the G string, and ring finger on the third fret of the B string — the standard D Minor shape — then add your pinky to the third fret of the high E string wait, let us be more precise: a common Dm6 voicing places the index finger on the first fret of the B string instead of the high E, allowing the open B string to provide the sixth. Experiment with Dm6 followed by A7 and then Dm to hear the classic minor key ii-V-i resolution that this chord often participates in.',
  'Index: B string, fret 1 | Middle: G string, fret 2 | Ring: high e string, fret 2 | Open: D | Mute: low E, A',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765155/Dm6_xmuygu.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'Ddim',
  'Ddim (D Diminished) is one of the most dramatic and tension-filled chords in music. Its unstable, dissonant sound creates anticipation that demands resolution to a nearby chord.',
  'Ddim is built from three notes: D (root), F (minor third), and Ab (diminished fifth). Every interval in a diminished chord is a minor third, which means the notes are stacked in perfect symmetrical tension — this is what gives diminished chords their uniquely unsettling, unresolved character. The diminished fifth (tritone) interval between D and Ab was historically called the diabolus in musica — the devil in music — because of how dissonant and unstable it sounds. In tonal harmony, Ddim naturally wants to resolve upward to Eb Major or downward to C Major, making it a powerful passing chord. Diminished chords appear in classical music, jazz, blues, and rock wherever dramatic tension and resolution are desired. Understanding Ddim is an important step toward understanding more advanced harmony.',
  'A simple open position Ddim voicing: place your index finger on the first fret of the B string, your middle finger on the second fret of the D string, and your ring finger on the second fret of the G string. Strum only the D, G, and B strings. Listen to the dissonant, tense sound of the chord, then immediately play a D Major or C Major chord after it — hear how the resolution feels almost like a release of held breath. This tension-resolution movement is the essence of what diminished chords do musically. Practice inserting Ddim as a passing chord between C Major and D Minor to hear a classic chromatic passing chord movement.',
  'Index: B string, fret 1 | Middle: D string, fret 2 | Ring: G string, fret 2 | Strum: D, G, B strings only',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765136/Ddim_infddt.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'Edim',
  'Edim (E Diminished) is a tense, dramatic chord with a naturally unresolved sound. It resolves most naturally to F Major and is a powerful tool for creating harmonic tension.',
  'Edim is built from three notes: E (root), G (minor third), and Bb (diminished fifth). Like all diminished chords, it is constructed entirely from stacked minor third intervals, which gives it that characteristic symmetrical tension and instability. The tritone between E and Bb is particularly stark — Bb is a dissonant half-step away from the B natural that defines E Minor, making Edim sound significantly more tense than its minor chord neighbor. Edim resolves naturally to F Major, making it the vii° chord in the key of F Major — a very common harmonic function. In jazz, diminished chords are also used as chromatic passing chords between more stable harmonies. In classical and romantic era music, diminished chords are frequently used to heighten dramatic tension before a resolution. Edim also appears as the vii° chord in the key of E Minor when used in a harmonic minor context.',
  'A practical open position Edim: place your index finger on the first fret of the D string and your middle finger on the first fret of the G string. Strum the D, G, and B strings only — the open B string provides the Bb... wait, B natural is not Bb. A cleaner approach: the most common Edim voicing places the index finger on the second fret of the D string, middle finger on the third fret of the A string, and ring finger on the third fret of the B string. Strum from the A string down. Play Edim followed immediately by F Major and listen carefully to the resolution — this is one of the clearest examples of harmonic tension and release you can hear on guitar.',
  'Middle: A string, fret 3 | Index: D string, fret 2 | Ring: B string, fret 3 | Strum: A, D, G, B strings',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765137/Edim_u9eupi.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'Dsus4',
  'Dsus4 is a suspended chord with an open, unresolved sound. It is one of the most commonly used chords in rock and pop, often ringing out before resolving to D Major.',
  'Dsus4 is built from three notes: D (root), G (perfect fourth), and A (perfect fifth). The term "suspended" refers to the fact that the third of the chord — F# in D Major — is replaced by the fourth (G). This removal of the third leaves the chord with an ambiguous, gender-neutral quality: it is neither major nor minor. Instead it has an open, hovering feeling that creates gentle tension wanting to resolve. The most natural resolution is to D Major (where the G drops back down to F#) or D Minor (where the G drops to F). The sus4-to-major resolution is one of the most satisfying sounds in all of guitar music and is heard in countless well-known songs. Dsus4 to D Major is a movement that guitarists use constantly for strumming embellishment, particularly on acoustic guitar where the sound rings out beautifully.',
  'Dsus4 is almost identical to D Major — the only change is lifting your index finger off the G string and replacing it with your ring finger (or pinky) on the third fret of the B string. Standard Dsus4 fingering: place your ring finger on the third fret of the B string, middle finger on the second fret of the G string, and index finger on the second fret of the high E string. The open D string is your bass root. Strum from the D string down. Now practice the iconic Dsus4 to D Major movement: play Dsus4, then lift your pinky to reveal D Major. This resolving motion is one of the most satisfying sounds in acoustic guitar playing and appears in countless songs.',
  'Ring: B string, fret 3 | Middle: G string, fret 2 | Index: high e string, fret 2 | Open: D | Mute: low E, A',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765135/Dsus4_qkku2b.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'E Major',
  'One of the first chords every guitarist learns. E Major uses all six strings and produces a full, resonant sound that works in rock, blues, country, and folk.',
  'The E Major chord is built from three notes: E (root), G# (major third), and B (perfect fifth). Because the guitar is tuned with E as its lowest string, this chord rings out with exceptional fullness and depth. It is one of the few open chords that uses every string on the guitar, giving it a powerful, wall-of-sound quality. E Major appears in countless songs across virtually every genre and is often one of the very first chords a beginner learns because of its approachable finger shape and immediate payoff. Common progressions using E Major include E-A-B (a classic rock I-IV-V) and E-C#m-A-B which appears in many pop and rock songs.',
  'Keep your fingers arched so they do not accidentally mute the open B and high E strings — this is the most common beginner mistake with this chord. Place your index finger on the first fret of the G string, your middle finger on the second fret of the A string, and your ring finger on the second fret of the D string. Press your thumb firmly but gently against the back of the neck for stability. Strum slowly from the low E string downward and listen for any muted or buzzing strings before playing up to speed.',
  'Index: G string, fret 1 | Middle: A string, fret 2 | Ring: D string, fret 2 | Open: E, B, high e',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765139/EMaj_mtebfm.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'E Minor',
  'The easiest chord on the guitar. E Minor has a dark, melancholic sound and is used in virtually every genre from classical to metal.',
  'E Minor is a two-finger chord built from the notes E (root), G (minor third), and B (perfect fifth). The minor third interval — G instead of G# — is what gives it that characteristic dark, introspective quality compared to E Major. Because it only requires two fingers and uses all six open strings, it is widely considered the most beginner-friendly chord on the guitar. Despite its simplicity, E Minor is incredibly versatile. It is the foundation of countless classic songs and serves as a gateway to understanding the difference between major and minor tonality. It also transitions smoothly to and from G Major, D Major, and C Major, making it a staple of the open chord toolkit.',
  'This is a great chord to start with if your fingers are still building strength. Place your middle finger on the second fret of the A string and your ring finger on the second fret of the D string. Every other string rings open. Focus on pressing directly behind the fret, not on top of it, to get a clean sound without buzzing. Practice transitioning between E Minor and E Major to train your ear to recognize the difference between major and minor tonality.',
  'Middle: A string, fret 2 | Ring: D string, fret 2 | Open: E, G, B, high e',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765134/Em_rtuitl.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'A Major',
  'A bright, versatile open chord. A Major is one of the most commonly used chords in popular music and pairs naturally with E and D Major.',
  'A Major is built from the notes A (root), C# (major third), and E (perfect fifth). In open position, all three fretted notes sit on the second fret across the D, G, and B strings, which means your fingers need to be neatly stacked in a row — a technique that takes a little practice but becomes second nature quickly. A Major has a bright, happy sound and is a cornerstone of country, pop, and rock music. It appears in the I-IV-V progression alongside D and E, which is arguably the most common chord progression in popular music. Learning A Major also lays the groundwork for understanding barre chord shapes later on, since the A Major shape is the foundation for barring at higher frets.',
  'The trickiest part of A Major is fitting three fingers onto the second fret without muting adjacent strings. Try using your index, middle, and ring fingers across the D, G, and B strings. Some players prefer to use a mini-barre with their ring finger across all three strings at the second fret — experiment to find what feels natural. Avoid strumming the low E string as it is not part of the chord. The open A string is your bass note and the open high E string should ring freely.',
  'Index: D string, fret 2 | Middle: G string, fret 2 | Ring: B string, fret 2 | Open: A, high e | Mute: low E',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765150/AMaj_neuv6c.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'A Minor',
  'A Minor is one of the most expressive open chords on the guitar. Its melancholic, emotional quality makes it a favorite in ballads, classical pieces, and rock.',
  'A Minor is built from the notes A (root), C (minor third), and E (perfect fifth). It is closely related to C Major — they share two of the same three notes — making transitions between them smooth and natural. A Minor has a deeply emotional, somewhat wistful sound that lends itself well to slower, more introspective music. The chord shape is similar to E Major shifted across one string, so players who already know E Major will find A Minor approachable. It is also the relative minor of C Major, meaning both keys share the same set of notes, which is an important music theory concept to understand as you advance. Songs in A Minor or that feature A Minor prominently include classics from virtually every genre.',
  'Place your index finger on the first fret of the B string, your middle finger on the second fret of the D string, and your ring finger on the second fret of the G string. The open A and high E strings ring freely, while the low E string should be muted or avoided. A common beginner mistake is letting the ring finger accidentally touch the high E string — focus on keeping your fingers arched. Practice the A Minor to C Major transition as it is one of the most useful chord changes in all of music.',
  'Index: B string, fret 1 | Middle: D string, fret 2 | Ring: G string, fret 2 | Open: A, high e | Mute: low E',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765138/Am_hxdjnt.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'D Major',
  'D Major has a bright, jangly sound that cuts through a mix. It is one of the most popular chords in folk, country, pop, and acoustic rock.',
  'D Major is built from the notes D (root), F# (major third), and A (perfect fifth). It is a three-string chord played on the D, G, B, and high E strings — the low E and A strings are not played. D Major has a characteristic brightness and chime that makes it stand out in a mix, especially on acoustic guitar. It forms the backbone of the I-IV-V progression in the key of D alongside G and A Major, and appears in an enormous number of classic songs. The D Major chord shape is also important because it introduces players to the concept of muting strings that are not part of the chord, which becomes increasingly important as chords get more complex.',
  'Place your index finger on the second fret of the G string, your middle finger on the second fret of the high E string, and your ring finger on the third fret of the B string. The open D string is your bass root note — make sure it rings clearly. Practice strumming from the D string down and avoid accidentally catching the A or low E strings. The triangular shape of D Major becomes very recognizable with practice. Focus on keeping all four notes clean and buzz-free before worrying about speed.',
  'Index: G string, fret 2 | Middle: high e string, fret 2 | Ring: B string, fret 3 | Open: D | Mute: low E, A',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765133/DMaj_izqbkj.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'D Minor',
  'D Minor carries a mournful, dramatic quality that makes it one of the most emotionally evocative chords on the guitar.',
  'D Minor is built from the notes D (root), F (minor third), and A (perfect fifth). The difference between D Major and D Minor is a single note — the third drops from F# to F — but the emotional shift is dramatic. While D Major sounds bright and uplifting, D Minor carries a sadness and weight that makes it indispensable in ballads, classical pieces, and dramatic musical moments. Like D Major, only the top four strings are played. D Minor is the relative minor of F Major and appears frequently alongside A Minor and C Major in common progressions. It was famously described as the saddest of all keys in the mockumentary Spinal Tap, a sentiment that resonates with many guitarists.',
  'Place your index finger on the first fret of the high E string, your middle finger on the second fret of the G string, and your ring finger on the third fret of the B string. The open D string is your bass root note. Strum from the D string downward only — the A and low E strings are not part of this chord. This is a compact, efficient chord shape that will feel comfortable in the hand once you develop some calluses. Practice transitioning between D Minor and A Minor as they are very common chord partners.',
  'Index: high e string, fret 1 | Middle: G string, fret 2 | Ring: B string, fret 3 | Open: D | Mute: low E, A',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765133/Dm_zutlcu.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'G Major',
  'G Major is one of the most commonly used chords in all of music. Its rich, open sound makes it ideal for strumming on acoustic guitar.',
  'G Major is built from the notes G (root), B (major third), and D (perfect fifth). The open position G Major chord uses all six strings and has a wonderfully full and resonant sound because it utilizes multiple open strings. It is one of the most popular guitar chords in folk, country, pop, and rock, appearing in countless well-known songs. There are a few different fingering options for G Major — some players use three fingers with their pinky anchoring the high E string, while others use four fingers for a slightly different voicing. The version that places the pinky on the high E string (fret 3) along with the ring finger on the low E is considered the standard open chord shape and is strongly recommended because it sets up smooth transitions to other chords like C Major and D Major.',
  'The recommended fingering is: middle finger on the low E string at fret 3, index finger on the A string at fret 2, and ring finger on the B string at fret 3, pinky on the high E string at fret 3. All other strings ring open. The two most important notes to get clean are the low E (your bass root) and the high E — both require firm finger pressure to avoid muffled sound. G Major to C Major is one of the most important transitions in beginner guitar, so drill that chord change until it feels automatic.',
  'Middle: low E string, fret 3 | Index: A string, fret 2 | Ring: B string, fret 3 | Pinky: high e string, fret 3 | Open: D, G',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772748971/GMaj_kjj3pr.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'C Major',
  'C Major is a cornerstone of music theory and one of the most widely used chords on guitar. It has a warm, open, and universally pleasing sound.',
  'C Major is built from the notes C (root), E (major third), and G (perfect fifth). On guitar, the open position C Major chord is one of the first chords most students learn and one of the trickiest to play cleanly because the fingers need to stretch across multiple strings while keeping the open strings unobstructed. C Major is the key with no sharps or flats, making it musically fundamental and theoretically important for understanding scales, chords, and how music works. It transitions naturally with A Minor (its relative minor), G Major, F Major, and D Minor, making it the anchor chord in many of the most common progressions in popular music. C Major is also notable for being the foundation chord from which many learners first begin to understand music theory.',
  'Place your ring finger on the third fret of the A string, your middle finger on the second fret of the D string, and your index finger on the first fret of the B string. The G and high E strings ring open, and the low E string should be muted. Keeping your ring finger firmly pressing the A string at fret 3 is critical — this is your bass root note and must ring clearly. Many beginners accidentally mute the open G string with their middle finger, so focus on arching your fretting hand. Practice the C Major to G Major transition — it is one of the most common in all of popular music.',
  'Ring: A string, fret 3 | Middle: D string, fret 2 | Index: B string, fret 1 | Open: G, high e | Mute: low E',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765137/C_wipk0s.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'F Major',
  'F Major is the first barre chord most guitarists tackle. Mastering it is a significant milestone that unlocks the ability to play barre chords across the entire fretboard.',
  'F Major is built from the notes F (root), A (major third), and C (perfect fifth). In its standard form, it is played as a full barre chord at the first fret — the index finger lays across all six strings while the remaining fingers form an E Major shape behind it. This is a physically demanding chord because the first fret requires the most finger strength of any position on the neck. Many beginners spend weeks or even months developing the hand strength and technique to play F Major cleanly. However, once mastered, the barre chord shape becomes a moveable tool that can be shifted to any fret to produce any major chord — making it one of the single most valuable techniques in guitar. F Major also appears frequently in C Major-based progressions as the IV chord.',
  'Bar all six strings with your index finger at the first fret. Then place your ring finger on the third fret of the A string, your pinky on the third fret of the D string, and your middle finger on the second fret of the G string. The most common difficulty is getting the high E and B strings to ring clearly through the barre. Try rolling your index finger slightly toward the headstock so the bony side of your finger does the pressing. Build up strength gradually — starting with a partial barre on just the top two strings before attempting the full chord is a valid practice approach.',
  'Index: full barre at fret 1 | Middle: G string, fret 2 | Ring: A string, fret 3 | Pinky: D string, fret 3',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765132/FMaj_bz6lhh.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'B Minor',
  'B Minor is an essential intermediate chord used constantly in pop, rock, and country. It is typically played as a partial barre at the second fret.',
  'B Minor is built from the notes B (root), D (minor third), and F# (perfect fifth). It is typically played as a partial barre chord at the second fret using the A-Major-shaped barre form. B Minor is one of the most frequently encountered chords in popular music because it is the ii chord in the key of A Major and the vi chord in the key of D Major — two of the most guitar-friendly keys. Songs in the key of D, A, or G will commonly feature B Minor as a key harmonic element. It has a somewhat brooding, introspective sound that works beautifully in slower songs and emotional passages. Mastering B Minor is considered a significant milestone because it combines barre technique with a more complex three-finger shape.',
  'Barre your index finger across the top five strings at the second fret (muting the low E string). Place your middle finger on the second fret of the high E string, your ring finger on the fourth fret of the A string... wait, that is the full barre version. The most commonly taught version: index finger barres strings 1-5 at fret 2, ring finger on fret 4 of the D string, pinky on fret 4 of the G string, middle finger on fret 3 of the B string. Make sure the low E string is either muted or avoided. Clean execution of the barre is the key — use your thumb positioned behind your middle finger for maximum leverage.',
  'Index: partial barre frets 1-5 at fret 2 | Middle: B string, fret 3 | Ring: D string, fret 4 | Pinky: G string, fret 4 | Mute: low E',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765140/Bm_tpdh5h.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'A7',
  'A7 is a dominant seventh chord with a bluesy, tension-filled sound. It is one of the most useful chords in blues and folk music and is easy to play.',
  'A7 is built from the notes A (root), C# (major third), E (perfect fifth), and G (minor seventh). The addition of the minor seventh interval gives the chord its characteristic tension and sense of wanting to resolve — this is the defining quality of dominant seventh chords. In the key of D, A7 functions as the V7 chord and creates a strong pull toward the D Major resolution, a relationship known as a perfect cadence. A7 is one of the easiest seventh chords to play because it only requires one or two fingers in open position. Its blues-infused sound is heard in countless folk, country, and blues songs, and it is an excellent introduction to the world of seventh chord colors and tension-resolution.',
  'The simplest version of A7: place only your index finger on the second fret of the D string. The open A, G, B, and high E strings all ring freely, and the low E is muted. This is a satisfying chord to learn early because with just one finger you get a rich four-note chord. A slightly fuller voicing adds the middle finger on the second fret of the B string. Practice using A7 in a progression: A7 resolving to D Major is one of the most satisfying sounds in acoustic guitar playing.',
  'Index: D string, fret 2 | Open: A, G, B, high e | Mute: low E',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765130/A7_aszzgg.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'D7',
  'D7 adds a bluesy, jazzy tension to the D chord. It is widely used in blues, folk, and jazz and resolves beautifully to G Major.',
  'D7 is built from the notes D (root), F# (major third), A (perfect fifth), and C (minor seventh). Like all dominant seventh chords, D7 creates harmonic tension that naturally wants to resolve — in this case, to G Major. This V7-I relationship (D7 to G) is one of the most fundamental harmonic movements in Western music. D7 has a slightly more complex sound than D Major — it retains the brightness of D Major but adds a bluesy edge that gives it real character. It is common in blues chord progressions where the I, IV, and V chords are often played as dominant sevenths, and it appears frequently in jazz and folk music. The shape is very similar to D Major with only one finger change.',
  'Compared to D Major, D7 swaps out the middle finger on the high E string for an open string and adds the index finger on the first fret of the B string — wait, let us be precise. Place your index finger on the first fret of the B string, your middle finger on the second fret of the G string, and your ring finger on the second fret of the high E string. The open D and A strings form the bass. Mute the low E string. The key difference from D Major is the C note on the B string, which is the minor seventh that creates the dominant character of the chord.',
  'Index: B string, fret 1 | Middle: G string, fret 2 | Ring: high e string, fret 2 | Open: D | Mute: low E, A',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765135/D7_hnd2v8.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'G Minor',
  'G Minor is a deeply expressive chord with a dark, rich quality. It appears frequently in pop, R&B, and rock, especially in minor key songs.',
  'G Minor is built from the notes G (root), Bb (minor third), and D (perfect fifth). Open position G Minor is one of the more challenging beginner chords because it requires a barre at the third fret for its full voicing, though a simplified open version exists. G Minor has a notably darker, more brooding sound than G Major and is commonly found in songs written in minor keys. It is the i chord in the key of G Minor and the vi chord in the key of Bb Major. G Minor pairs naturally with Eb Major, Bb Major, D Minor, and F Major in common minor key progressions. Understanding G Minor helps build the conceptual framework for understanding how minor chords function within a key.',
  'For the simplified open voicing: place your index finger on the first fret of the low E string, your middle finger on the third fret of the A string, ring finger on the third fret of the D string, and your pinky on the third fret of the high E string. The open G string rings freely as a root note. For a cleaner full voicing, many players use the barre form at the third fret using the E-minor barre shape. Focus on getting the bass notes on the low E and A strings ringing clearly as they anchor the chord sound.',
  'Index: low E string, fret 1 | Middle: A string, fret 3 | Ring: D string, fret 3 | Pinky: high e string, fret 3 | Open: G',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765131/Gm_phqitq.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'C Minor',
  'C Minor is a powerful, emotive chord used across pop, rock, and classical music. Played as a barre chord at the third fret, it builds essential barre chord technique.',
  'C Minor is built from the notes C (root), Eb (minor third), and G (perfect fifth). In standard playing it is most often performed as a barre chord using the A-minor shape at the third fret. C Minor has a heavy, serious quality — it is a chord that commands attention. It is the i chord in the key of C Minor (a very common key in classical and pop music) and the vi chord in the key of Eb Major. C Minor appears in countless well-known songs across genres and is a key stepping stone between beginner open chords and the fully moveable barre chord vocabulary. Mastering C Minor means mastering the A-minor-shape barre, which can then be moved to any fret to produce any minor chord.',
  'Barre your index finger across the top five strings at the third fret (muting the low E string). Then place your ring finger on the fifth fret of the A string and your pinky on the fifth fret of the D string. This is the A-minor barre chord shape. The key challenge is getting all five strings of the barre to ring clearly, particularly the G and high E strings. Move your thumb to directly behind your index finger on the back of the neck for maximum leverage. Start slowly and check each note individually before strumming the full chord.',
  'Index: partial barre strings 1-5 at fret 3 | Ring: A string, fret 5 | Pinky: D string, fret 5 | Mute: low E',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765131/Cm_p0ej6p.svg',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'E7',
  'E7 is a dominant seventh chord with a warm, bluesy character. It is nearly identical to open E Major with one finger lifted, making it very beginner-friendly.',
  'E7 is built from the notes E (root), G# (major third), B (perfect fifth), and D (minor seventh). The D note on the open D string is what gives E7 its dominant seventh color. In the key of A, E7 is the V7 chord and creates a powerful tension that resolves beautifully to A Major or A Minor. This tension and resolution is the harmonic heartbeat of blues music, and E7 is one of the most-used chords in the blues genre. The transition from E to E7 is remarkably easy — you simply lift one finger — making it a satisfying early win for beginners and a great introduction to the concept of chord extensions. E7 is heard in blues, folk, country, and rock constantly.',
  'From the standard open E Major shape, simply lift your index finger off the G string so it rings open. Your middle and ring fingers stay on the A and D strings at the second fret. The open G string now creates the D note that gives the chord its seventh character. Strum all six strings. Practice moving back and forth between E Major and E7 — the difference in sound is significant but the physical movement is tiny. This is a great chord for understanding how small changes create big tonal shifts.',
  'Middle: A string, fret 2 | Ring: D string, fret 2 | Open: E, G (7th), B, high e',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765153/E7_qewvqk.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO chords (title, description, details, tips, finger_positions, image_url, difficulty) VALUES (
  'Esus4',
  'Esus4 is an open, resonant suspended chord that creates gentle tension before resolving to E Major or E Minor. It is widely used in rock, pop, and folk for strumming embellishment.',
  'Esus4 is built from three notes: E (root), A (perfect fourth), and B (perfect fifth). Like all suspended fourth chords, the third is replaced by the fourth — meaning the G# that defines E Major is swapped out for an A. This leaves the chord tonally ambiguous: neither major nor minor, just open and hovering. Esus4 has a particularly full, ringing quality on guitar because it uses five strings including several open ones. The natural resolution of Esus4 is to E Major (where the A drops back to G#) or E Minor (where the A drops to G). The Esus4 to E Major movement is one of the most satisfying resolving motions in all of guitar music and is heard constantly in classic rock, pop, and acoustic music. Pete Townshend of The Who famously built entire anthemic guitar parts around suspended chord resolutions, and Esus4 is central to that vocabulary.',
  'Esus4 is extremely close to open E Major — the only change is adding your pinky to the second fret of the A string. Standard Esus4 fingering: place your middle finger on the second fret of the A string, ring finger on the second fret of the D string, and add your pinky to the second fret of the B string. The open E, G, and high E strings all ring freely. Strum all six strings. Now practice the resolving motion: play Esus4, then lift your pinky off the B string to land on E Major. Feel and hear the resolution as the suspended fourth (A) on the B string drops to the major third (G#) on the open string. Drilling this back-and-forth movement is one of the best strumming embellishment exercises a beginner can do.',
  'Middle: A string, fret 2 | Ring: D string, fret 2 | Pinky: B string, fret 2 | Open: E, G, high e',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765155/Esus4_iwlq5p.svg',
  'BEGINNER'
);

-- SCALES

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'A Minor Pentatonic',
  'The most important scale in rock and blues guitar. The A Minor Pentatonic Position 1 is the foundation of improvisation and the starting point for nearly every lead guitarist.',
  'The A Minor Pentatonic scale contains five notes: A, C, D, E, and G. It is derived from the A Natural Minor scale by removing the second (B) and sixth (F) intervals, leaving only the notes that sound strong and consonant against minor chord progressions. Position 1 — the most commonly taught shape — begins on the 5th fret of the low E string and contains three root notes forming a triangular pattern on the fretboard: one on the low E string, one on the D string, and one on the high E string. This scale is used in virtually every style of guitar-based music: rock, blues, metal, country, and more. Famous solos built primarily around this scale include works by Eric Clapton, Jimmy Page, Jimi Hendrix, and countless others. It is the single most important scale a beginner guitarist can learn for soloing and improvisation.',
  'Start on the 5th fret root note (A) on the low E string and ascend string by string using alternate picking. Your index finger covers all notes on the 5th fret and your pinky covers all notes on the 8th fret — use your ring finger for the notes in between on the D and G strings. Practice going up and down the scale slowly with a metronome before trying to play licks. Once comfortable with the shape, try playing it over an A Minor backing track and experiment with bending the notes on the G and B strings at the 7th and 8th frets — this is where the blues magic happens.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765190/am-pent-scale_k1o3ij.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 5',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'E Minor Pentatonic',
  'E Minor Pentatonic is one of the most natural scales for guitar and unlocks a huge vocabulary of rock and blues licks. At the 12th fret, it delivers a bright, cutting tone ideal for expressive lead playing.',
  'The E Minor Pentatonic scale contains five notes: E, G, A, B, and D. It shares the exact same shape as A Minor Pentatonic — the only difference is the root note, which changes where on the neck you anchor the pattern. Position 1 at the 12th fret is the octave equivalent of the open position, meaning you are playing the exact same notes but one octave higher. This position is particularly popular for lead guitar because the higher frets produce a brighter, more cutting tone that sits well in a mix. The 12th fret is also a natural landmark on the neck — it is where the fretboard repeats — making it an intuitive reference point for players learning to navigate the guitar. Many iconic rock and blues solos are played in this position because of the expressive bending and vibrato opportunities it offers.',
  'At the 12th fret your index finger covers all notes on the 12th fret and your pinky covers all notes on the 15th fret — use your ring finger for the 14th fret notes on the D and G strings. String bending is very natural in this position: try a full step bend on the G string at the 14th fret, pushing the string upward toward the ceiling. This is one of the most commonly used bends in all of rock guitar. Practice starting and ending every run on an E note — either the 12th fret of the low E string or the 12th fret of the high E string — to reinforce your sense of the tonal center. Then try the same scale pattern at the open position and compare the tonal difference between the two octaves.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765189/em-pent-scale_cufpdy.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 12',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'C Major Scale',
  'The C Major scale is the most fundamental scale in Western music theory. Learning it on guitar builds fretboard knowledge and unlocks your understanding of how music works.',
  'The C Major scale contains seven notes: C, D, E, F, G, A, and B. It is unique because it contains no sharps or flats, making it the theoretical starting point for understanding keys, intervals, modes, and chord construction. Every major scale follows the same interval pattern: Whole-Whole-Half-Whole-Whole-Whole-Half steps. C Major is the best scale to learn this pattern because it uses only natural notes. On guitar, Position 1 of the C Major scale is typically played starting at the third fret of the A string. Understanding C Major also unlocks the relationship between major and minor keys — A Minor is the relative minor of C Major, meaning they share all the same notes. The chords built from the C Major scale — C, Dm, Em, F, G, Am, Bdim — are among the most common chord progressions in all of popular music.',
  'Practice the C Major scale slowly with a metronome, paying attention to finger placement. Use one finger per fret — index for fret 3 notes, middle for fret 4 notes, ring for fret 5 notes, and pinky for fret 6 notes. This one-finger-per-fret technique is foundational and will serve you throughout your entire guitar journey. As you practice, try to sing or hum along with each note — this builds your ear alongside your technique. Once you can play the scale cleanly, try improvising simple melodies over a C Major or A Minor chord progression.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765189/cmaj-scale_vwmgmn.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 3',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'G Major Scale',
  'G Major is one of the most commonly used keys in guitar music. Its scale position covers an area of the fretboard that feels natural and comfortable for most players.',
  'The G Major scale contains seven notes: G, A, B, C, D, E, and F#. It is one of the most guitar-friendly keys due to the presence of multiple open strings that align with scale notes. G Major shares a key signature with E Minor (its relative minor), and songs in both of these keys are enormously common in folk, country, rock, and pop. The chords built from G Major — G, Am, Bm, C, D, Em, F#dim — include some of the most commonly played chords on guitar. Understanding G Major deeply helps you connect your knowledge of open chords (G, C, D, Em, Am) to the underlying scale they all come from. Position 1 on guitar starts at the third fret and covers a two-octave range that connects smoothly to related positions.',
  'Pay close attention to the F# note in this scale — it is the one note that distinguishes G Major from C Major, and hitting it cleanly in context gives your melodies a strong sense of the G Major key. Practice the scale ascending and descending, then try picking out simple melodies you know — Happy Birthday, for example, can be played starting from the G note on the low E string. Connecting scale practice to real melodies accelerates learning dramatically. Also practice the scale over a G Major chord drone to hear how each note sounds against the root chord.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765188/gmaj-scale_kvehcc.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 3',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'A Major Pentatonic',
  'A Major Pentatonic is the bright, uplifting counterpart to A Minor Pentatonic. It is widely used in country, blues, and rock for happy, melodic lead playing.',
  'The A Major Pentatonic scale contains five notes: A, B, C#, E, and F#. It is derived from the A Major scale by removing the fourth (D) and seventh (G#) intervals. Major Pentatonic has a noticeably brighter, more optimistic sound compared to its minor counterpart and is the scale of choice for country lead guitar, classic rock solos with a positive energy, and many blues players who want to create a major-key feel. Interestingly, A Major Pentatonic and F# Minor Pentatonic contain the exact same notes — they are relative pentatonic scales, just as A Major and F# Minor are relative keys. Position 1 of A Major Pentatonic starts at the second fret of the low E string, three frets below where the A Minor Pentatonic pattern begins.',
  'A useful trick: A Major Pentatonic Position 1 uses the exact same shape as A Minor Pentatonic Position 1, just shifted down three frets (from fret 5 to fret 2). This means once you know the minor pentatonic shape, you already know the major pentatonic shape — just in a different position. Experiment by playing both over an A Major backing track and notice how the major pentatonic sounds resolved and bright while the minor pentatonic sounds more tense and bluesy. Many great solos blend both scales for emotional contrast.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765187/amaj-pent-scale_vjf36x.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 2',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'D Major Scale',
  'D Major is an extremely common guitar key with a bright, resonant sound. Its scale position on the fretboard connects naturally with many open chord shapes.',
  'The D Major scale contains seven notes: D, E, F#, G, A, B, and C#. The key of D Major has two sharps (F# and C#) and is one of the most popular keys for guitar playing due to the presence of open string resonances. Many iconic guitar-based songs are written in D Major or use its chords heavily. The chords in D Major — D, Em, F#m, G, A, Bm, C#dim — include several of the most commonly played guitar chords. Position 1 of the D Major scale typically starts around the fifth fret area and gives players access to a comfortable two-octave range. Understanding D Major deeply also helps with understanding Bm (its relative minor) and sets the stage for learning the B Minor Pentatonic scale.',
  'Because D Major shares notes with both G Major and A Major, practicing these three related major scales back to back is excellent for building fretboard fluency. When practicing D Major, pay attention to the C# note — it is the leading tone that creates the strong sense of resolution when you reach the root D. Try to solo over a simple D-G-A chord progression using only the D Major scale and notice how naturally the notes fit. This is a great exercise for connecting scale knowledge to practical musical application.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765186/dmaj-scale_rgd8pr.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 5',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'B Minor Pentatonic',
  'B Minor Pentatonic is the go-to scale for soloing in the key of D Major. Its positions on the fretboard pair perfectly with common D, G, and A chord progressions.',
  'The B Minor Pentatonic scale contains five notes: B, D, E, F#, and A. It is the relative minor pentatonic scale of D Major Pentatonic, meaning both scales share the exact same notes. B Minor Pentatonic is commonly used when playing over songs in the key of D or when a minor feel is desired in that key area. Position 1 begins at the seventh fret of the low E string. The seventh fret is a comfortable position on the neck where many players feel relaxed and have good control. B Minor Pentatonic is frequently combined with D Major Pentatonic by experienced players — switching between the two over the same chord progression creates a dynamic contrast between minor tension and major brightness.',
  'Playing at the seventh fret means your hand is in the middle of the neck where the frets are closer together than in open position — many players find this easier on their fingers. Use your index finger on all seventh-fret notes and your pinky on all tenth-fret notes. Since B Minor Pentatonic and D Major Pentatonic share the same notes, practice playing the same lick starting from both the B root note and the D root note to hear how the same notes create different feelings depending on which note you emphasize.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765185/bm-pent-scale_uoevgi.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 7',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'A Natural Minor Scale',
  'The A Natural Minor scale is the foundation of minor key music on guitar. It provides the full harmonic vocabulary for minor key songs and is the parent scale of A Minor Pentatonic.',
  'The A Natural Minor scale contains seven notes: A, B, C, D, E, F, and G. It is identical to the C Major scale — it uses all the same notes — but starts from A rather than C, giving it an entirely different harmonic character. While C Major sounds bright and resolved, A Natural Minor sounds darker and more melancholic. This relationship between a major scale and its relative minor is one of the most important concepts in music theory. The A Natural Minor scale is the parent scale of the A Minor Pentatonic — the pentatonic version simply removes the second (B) and sixth (F) notes. Understanding the full minor scale gives you access to two additional notes that add flavor and complexity to your solos, especially the F note which creates a characteristically dark, Spanish-sounding quality.',
  'Compare the A Natural Minor scale directly to the A Minor Pentatonic scale you already know. The pentatonic removes B and F — practice playing the full seven-note minor scale and then the five-note pentatonic version back to back to hear what those two notes add to the sound. The F note in particular is very expressive — try ending a phrase on the F note (eighth fret, A string or first fret, high E string) to hear its moody, dramatic quality. This exercise connects your scale knowledge to real sonic understanding.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765185/anat-minor-scale_gcfvdz.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 5',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'E Blues Scale',
  'The E Blues Scale adds the famous blue note to the E Minor Pentatonic, creating the essential sound of blues guitar. It is one of the most expressive scales available to a guitarist.',
  'The E Blues Scale contains six notes: E, G, A, Bb, B, and D. It is the E Minor Pentatonic scale with one additional note — the flat fifth, Bb (also called the blue note or tritone). This single added note is responsible for the tension, grit, and expressiveness that defines blues music. The Bb creates a dissonant, unstable feeling when played, which resolves powerfully when you move to the adjacent B natural note. This half-step movement between Bb and B is the signature sound of blues soloing. The E Blues Scale in open position is one of the most comfortable scales to play on guitar because it utilizes open strings and sits in a natural hand position near the nut. Virtually every blues guitarist in history has used this scale extensively.',
  'The blue note — Bb — is the key to making this scale sound authentically bluesy. Practice playing from A (open A string) up to Bb (first fret A string) and resolving to B (second fret A string). Feel the tension that the Bb creates and the resolution when you land on B. This is the emotional core of blues music in physical form. A great exercise is to play the E Minor Pentatonic scale ascending and then add the Bb as a passing note between the A and B notes on your way back down. Also try bending the string while on the Bb to add even more expressive character.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765184/e-blues-pent-scale_y5wont.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 5 | Fret 12',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'C Major Pentatonic',
  'C Major Pentatonic bridges music theory and lead guitar playing. Its notes connect directly to the open chords most beginners learn first, making it an ideal melodic tool.',
  'The C Major Pentatonic scale contains five notes: C, D, E, G, and A. It is derived from the C Major scale by removing the fourth (F) and seventh (B) intervals — the two notes most likely to clash with major chord voicings. C Major Pentatonic is the relative major pentatonic scale of A Minor Pentatonic, meaning they share all five notes. This relationship is musically powerful: when you play A Minor Pentatonic over a C Major chord, you are effectively playing C Major Pentatonic from a different starting point. Understanding this relativity dramatically expands your improvisational options. C Major Pentatonic has a clean, melodic sound with no dissonance, making it easy to play over C Major chord progressions without hitting any wrong notes.',
  'Since A Minor Pentatonic and C Major Pentatonic use the same notes, practice playing the same pattern but emphasizing the C notes instead of the A notes. Notice how the scale feels different and resolves differently when C is your target note versus A. Play over a C Major chord and try to land on C notes at the start and end of your phrases — this is called targeting the root note and it is what separates random scale playing from actual melodic soloing. This concept — the same notes, different root — is one of the most important insights in all of lead guitar playing.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765183/cmaj-pent-scale_tnlcnl.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 3',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'D Minor Pentatonic',
  'D Minor Pentatonic is a staple of rock and blues guitar. Its position at the tenth fret sits in a comfortable, resonant area of the neck ideal for expressive bends and vibrato.',
  'The D Minor Pentatonic scale contains five notes: D, F, G, A, and C. It follows the same five-note minor pentatonic formula as A Minor Pentatonic, simply rooted on D. Position 1 begins at the tenth fret of the low E string. The higher position on the neck brings the frets closer together, making string bending easier and more controlled — a quality that experienced players exploit for expressive lead playing. D Minor Pentatonic is the relative minor pentatonic of F Major Pentatonic and is used extensively in rock songs written in D Minor or F Major. Many classic rock and metal songs use D Minor Pentatonic for their solos due to the powerful, aggressive sound it produces in the higher neck register.',
  'Playing at the tenth fret means you are in the upper register of the neck where the notes have a brighter, more cutting tone. String bends are easier here because the strings have less tension at higher frets — take advantage of this by practicing full-step bends on the G and B strings. Start slowly and make sure your bends reach the correct pitch: a full-step bend on the G string at the tenth fret should reach the pitch of the twelfth fret. Use your ring finger for bending and support it with your middle and index fingers behind it for additional leverage.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765182/dm-pent-scale_dmleyy.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 10',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'G Minor Pentatonic',
  'G Minor Pentatonic is a versatile and expressive scale commonly used in blues, soul, and rock. It sits in a comfortable hand position and works over a wide range of chord progressions.',
  'The G Minor Pentatonic scale contains five notes: G, Bb, C, D, and F. Rooted on G, it follows the universal minor pentatonic pattern and delivers the same dark, bluesy character as other minor pentatonic scales but with G as its tonal center. Position 1 begins at the third fret of the low E string, placing the hand in a very natural position near the lower frets. G Minor Pentatonic is the relative minor pentatonic of Bb Major Pentatonic. It is frequently used in funk, soul, and blues music. Songs in the key of G Minor or Bb Major commonly feature this scale prominently. Its flat-seventh note (F) and flat-third (Bb) give it a particularly bluesy flavor that works well in more groove-oriented styles.',
  'At the third fret position, you can incorporate open strings into your licks for added resonance. The open G string (your root note) can be used as a drone note beneath your scale playing, which is a great technique for building musical-sounding phrases. Practice playing phrases that begin or end on the open G string to reinforce the tonal center. Also practice the G Minor Pentatonic alongside G Major Pentatonic — the same shift in thinking that applies to A Minor/A Major Pentatonic applies here, and hearing both over a G chord is instructive.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765181/gm-pent-scale_se2w51.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 3',
  'BEGINNER'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'F Major Scale',
  'The F Major scale introduces one flat (Bb) and builds essential fretboard knowledge. It is a key stepping stone toward understanding flat keys and barre chord territory.',
  'The F Major scale contains seven notes: F, G, A, Bb, C, D, and E. It has one flat in its key signature — Bb — making it the next step after C Major for players learning their major scales. F Major is the IV chord in the key of C Major, so players who know C Major progressions will encounter F Major constantly. On guitar, F Major is typically played starting at the first fret, connecting to the same area of the neck where the F Major barre chord lives. Understanding F Major helps explain why the F barre chord exists where it does and gives lead players a complete set of notes to solo with in the key of F. D Minor is the relative minor of F Major, so soloists can also use D Minor Pentatonic over F Major progressions.',
  'The Bb note is the defining characteristic of F Major — it is the one note that separates it from C Major and G Major. Practice the scale and pay special attention to when you land on Bb, noticing how it creates a slightly darker color compared to C Major. Because F Major starts at the first fret, the frets are slightly more spread out and require more finger stretch. Use the one-finger-per-fret technique: index on fret 1, middle on fret 2, ring on fret 3, pinky on fret 4 — and shift where needed. This builds left-hand strength and dexterity significantly.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765181/fmaj-scale_bawdrt.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 1',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'A Dorian',
  'A Dorian is a minor mode with a distinctive raised sixth that gives it a sophisticated, funky edge. It is widely used in rock, jazz fusion, and funk lead guitar.',
  'A Dorian is the second mode of the G Major scale and contains seven notes: A, B, C, D, E, F#, and G. Compared to A Natural Minor, A Dorian has one note changed — the sixth is raised from F to F#. This single alteration gives Dorian its characteristic sound: it has the darkness of a minor scale but with a brighter, more sophisticated quality due to the raised sixth. The F# note is what creates the Dorian sound and distinguishes it from the Natural Minor. A Dorian is one of the most important modes in rock and jazz-fusion guitar. Carlos Santana built much of his signature sound around the Dorian mode, and it is heard extensively in songs by artists ranging from The Doors to Pink Floyd to Red Hot Chili Peppers. It works particularly well over minor seventh chord vamps.',
  'To understand A Dorian, start with the A Natural Minor scale you already know and simply raise the sixth note from F to F#. This is the only difference, but the sonic impact is significant. Practice playing A Natural Minor and A Dorian back to back and focus on the moment you hit the sixth degree — hear how F# sounds brighter and more sophisticated than F. A Dorian works best over Am7 chord vamps. Try playing the scale over a sustained Am7 chord and experiment with resolving phrases to the F# note to bring out the Dorian character. This is where modal playing begins to make sense.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765180/ador-scale_jhnpam.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 5',
  'INTERMEDIATE'
);

INSERT IGNORE INTO scales (title, description, details, tips, image_url, tab_url, position, difficulty) VALUES (
  'G Major Pentatonic',
  'G Major Pentatonic has a bright, country-inflected sound that works beautifully over G Major chord progressions. It pairs directly with the G Major open chord shape.',
  'The G Major Pentatonic scale contains five notes: G, A, B, D, and E. It is derived from the G Major scale by removing the fourth (C) and seventh (F#). G Major Pentatonic is the relative major pentatonic scale of E Minor Pentatonic — both share the same five notes, just with different root notes. This is musically powerful: the same pattern used for E Minor Pentatonic can be reinterpreted as G Major Pentatonic simply by emphasizing G as the tonal center. G Major Pentatonic has a warm, resonant quality and sits naturally in the hands at the third-fret position. It is extensively used in country music, classic rock, and folk guitar where a bright, melodic sound is desired. Knowing this scale also connects your pentatonic knowledge to the open chord shapes you already know in G.',
  'Since G Major Pentatonic and E Minor Pentatonic use the same notes, this is an excellent scale for practicing the concept of relative keys on the guitar. Play the same scale pattern but target G notes at the start and end of phrases instead of E notes. Over a G Major chord, land on G and B notes for the most resolved, stable sound. Over an Em chord, target E and G notes. This practical exercise trains your ear to hear the same notes in two completely different tonal contexts — a fundamental skill for all improvisers.',
  'https://res.cloudinary.com/dtbmua8x3/image/upload/fl_sanitize/v1772765179/gmaj-pent-scale_dzhq2k.svg',
  NULL,
  'Position 1 | Fret 3',
  'BEGINNER'
);

